The Ciompi Uprising|https://www.theflorentine.net/2025/07/31/the-ciompi-uprising/|Ciompi Uprising When Florence’s lowest-paid textile workers seized power, and how betrayal and ambition brought their revolution to a  ...    Unrest had been fomenting in Florence, especially in the Santa Croce and Oltrarno neighbourhoods, before it broke out into what started, at least in the beginning, as a bloodless coup on June 24, 1378, which was led by the humblest of workers in the cloth industry, including day labourers, wool combers, dyers and those doing poorly paid jobs like the many shop boys employed in the trade. Known as the Ciompi, deriving from the French word compère (meaning “buddy” or “pal”), they were considered a sort of “brotherhood”, except that they were excluded from becoming full members of the powerful and wealthy wool guild, which meant they could not benefit from most of its considerable privileges and perks. The revolt was sparked by the election of Salvestro de’ Medici, a cousin of the banking branch of the family, who was nominated gonfalonier by
